gmx:name.gco:CharacterString: Feature catalog for Express Lanes, California, 2015

gmx:scope.gco:CharacterString: High-occupancy vehicle lanes; Traffic engineering; Roads

gfc:definition.gco:CharacterString: Express Lanes - also known as High Occupancy Toll (HOT) lanes – are HOV lanes that may be accessed by single occupant vehicles by paying a toll.
The validated postmile values used by the State Highway System to determine the geographic extent of the record. It consists of each lane start and end points’ county code, route, and postmile.

Direction of Express lane: NB = Northbound; SB = Southbound; WB = Westbound; EB = Eastbound

gfc:label.gco:CharacterString: Direction: NB = Northbound; SB = Southbound; WB = Westbound; EB = Eastbound

gfc:definition.gco:CharacterString: The postmile at the beginning of the lane, including postmile prefix (The highway alignment code: C - Commercial truck, D - Duplicate postmile at meandering county line, G - Reposting of duplicate postmile at end of a route, H - Realignment of D mileage, L - Overlap postmile, M - Realignment of R mileage, N - Realignment of M mileage, R - First realignment, S - Spur, T - Temporary).
